metadata.name: Phantom Mask #6
metadata.description:
Multidimensional apparitions via mathematical geometric structures in the blockchain.
Figurative representational tradition meets code pattern ordering as dream-like robot heads. The tradition of face mask making and representation in modern art in dialogue with the ever changing all-possible computer programs and always present unforeseen glitch errors.
As a meta-language, the computer reads and mixes human and android facial features, as the automatic creation mimics its creator.
The robot generative portraits are a looking glass into the source code of the artwork.
Touch to voice the void of the hash.

Alexandre Rangel, 2022
www.alexandrerangel.art.br

metadata.name: Breakdown #151
metadata.description:
The key to solving a difficult problem is to break it down into a series of smaller, more tractable, problems.

Here we start with a rectangular polygon. We shrink our polygon by some fixed amount (inset), and then pick a point inside it. We then send off rays in N evenly spaced directions and use these to split the polygon into N new polygons. Repeat the process, varying parameters such as how we pick our point or the angles of our projected rays, and see what emerges.

Press 'v' to download an svg output.

The Incredible contraption is part of the fxhackathon 2023: co-creation interfaces.

Build, Iterate, Create

An attempt to give any collector a fun and powerful tool to create generative art and a new kind of minting experience.

metadata.name: Avaritia #70
metadata.description:
A third and final study of the human figure through code. Can a generative artwork be unsettling?  

If some don't resemble people, I apologize, and would be keen to refund or trade with you. This is partly the reason for releasing the work at low price. After spending a futile time trying to remove 'bad' outputs, I came to realize that's absolutely achievable, but at the expense of removing the surprise outputs.... The ones that kept me returning to this work over the course of 7 months. 

There's a second side to the low price.... I'd like this to be a small statement against greed within the generative art space over the last few years. Greed of artists ‚Äì greed of marketplaces ‚Äì greed of collectors ‚Äì greed of flippers. We were all too greedy. But there's a positive ending to my rant, because for us remainders, we're still here, down deep in digital art. 

Much love, and a small measuring of greed, 
Tenebris.Via 
2024


Additional params 
- &fullsize=true : Force output to occupy full screen width 
- &png=true : Download 2100x2970 png file 
- &svg=true : Download svg file 
- &theme={number} : Use "4" for plotter theme, with fixed-width black lines 
- &interval={number} : The higher the number, the less layers generated. Usually 4-16 
- &minlen={number} : Remove linepaths below {number} minimum length. Usually 50-500 
- &maxlen={number} : Remove linepaths above {number} maximum length. Usually 2000+ 

e.g. ?theme=4&interval=12&minlen=500

While the work is plottable, there can be a fair bit of trial and error to produce good results. Play around with the interval, minlen and maxlen params to suit. Inkscape is a great tool to help. 

Opensource libs 
- simplex noise implementation in JS : https://github.com/jwagner/simplex-noise.js 
- deterministic JS random methods : https://github.com/strainer/fdrandom.js 
- static indexer for 2D points : https://github.com/mourner/kdbush

metadata.name: ecolog√≠as - B #615
metadata.description:
ecolog√≠as - B

water is the medium where life first appeared in our planet. Water is also indispensable for the continuation of the life that emerged from - and with - it. The advent of AI species and their introduction into society is a new form of cambrian explosion. What is their medium? What is their water? How scarce and precious will it be for them? AI entities are not foreign to human resource necessities, though. The water that is essential to our human life will also be so for machines, as their energy still depends on our natural resources. Therefore, the ecologies of humans and machines will have, at least, the same elements as the ecologies of humans. AIs may help us reach better balances, only if we employ them to do so and if we teach them to help us.

ecolog√≠as-B is an entity that is part of a broader ecology. Released on occasion of the show "Unbound - Ecology in the Age of Machines" at Unit London. The data generated by this entity is read by a different piece minted on Ethereum, creating a link between Tezos and Ethereum, a metaphor for an ecology of blockchains.

it shares a common element with two other works released on fxhash: ecolog√≠as A and ecolog√≠as C, all of them contributing data to aforementioned pieces.

read more at https://www.iillucid.com/ecologias

15% of primary sales are donated to institutions working towards improving biodiversity and environmental efforts.

Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, @msoriaro

metadata.name: Glomularus #46
metadata.description:
Glomularus is an exploration in generative, artificial life forms. The project is an extension of my Protobyte series, begun in 2004.

Driven by Verlet icosahedra and responsive tendrils, Glomulari live in a spherical virtual ecosystem (V-eco) enhanced through user interaction.

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
  drag -> camera rotation
  drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
  scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
  1-9: add acceleration
  -, +: reduce | increase V-eco sphere radius
  f, g: reduce | increase fog
  p: screen capture

Tip:
To decrease creature acceleration, reduce V-eco sphere radius

Note:
Please post your favorite Glomularus screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: Until biodiversity rains #87
metadata.description:
Audiovisual generative artwork. 

In the interpretation of biological organisms, which break paradigms by doing something different, to adapt to changes and be able to survive, paths emerge to be imitated by so many, and make life flow. The development of the work is a metaphor for those paths full of ingenuity and risk, where colorful organisms in rows open trails, sliding like subtle drops, with sophisticated turns and elastic jumps.

Some alternative paths usually hide a message along the way. Literally, one could find and read phrases in relation to biodiversity and its importance. Although it is more common to ignore them, sometimes not respect them, or what is worse, forget them. Even so, in an exacerbated insistence, here, audiovisual organizations seem to be repeating themselves, ‚Äúuntil biodiversity rains‚Äù, and variety exploits so that ecosystems finally go it alone.


Relationship between visuals and sounds:
Biological organisms of different colors follow a path. They move forward, change shape, stop, turn. Always one after the other. At certain moments, they stretch and jump and sounds emerge.

Towards the edges of the canvas, the jumps are translated into cello sounds, mainly pizzicatos. Towards the center, the piano. From the main jumps emerges a kind of melody played by a pseudo-theremin-synth, characterized by flyaway melodies with glissant.


This artwork is 100% code, made in p5.js + tone.js.

[ Click ]  -> sound ON / OFF
[ s ] -> save 2160x2160px (in live view)
[ f ] -> fullscreen
[ p ] -> pause / play 

Note: This artwork is an animated piece, and requires a powerful GPU for optimal real-time playback. It is important to note that it may not run properly on mobile devices, especially not high-end ones.
It is recommended to run the piece in a new window from the ‚Äúopen‚Äù button.

metadata.name: Saccharin #29
metadata.description:
A continuation of my previous work but with a more minimalistic visual approach. Randomly generated primitive geometry are rendered as texture that undergoes a series of nodes to create a grayscale image. The texture is then colored with gradient map, layered with pixel noise to divide it into a randomly sized grid then subtly blurred in some areas to create a dreamy effect.

The resulting visual can seem vaguely familiar but at the same time can not be pinpointed to a specific time and place identity; it can vary between a Futurist painting look-alike to resembling an early 2000s colorful news bumper. Hazy memory slowly and constantly shifting, clouded vision taste artificially sweet, sometimes with a metallic aftertaste.

Just like saccharin.

----------
Press 'S' to capture a 3840x3840 screenshot of the current frame.
‚ö†Ô∏è Can be GPU extensive! ‚ö†Ô∏è

XALTED 2022

metadata.name: Botanical Ghosts #254
metadata.description:
This is a work about growth, impermanence and decay. Ghostly plants and flowers grow around an invisible point, but they immediately begin to fade into the dark background and are soon replaced and covered by others. This process of accumulation and disappearance builds an ever-changing floral garland, or perhaps a funeral wreath.

The monochrome vegetation is part of a fictional flora, born out of random algorithmic combinations, and does not intend to reproduce any real species. It belongs to an ‚Äúartificial nature‚Äù which, like so many worlds that the computers generate for us in movies, games, and virtual reality environments, is a convincing simulation of life, but it is not actually living. AI bots, virtual assistants and non-player characters are also representatives of the uncanny realm of the not-really-alive-but-looking-like-it, which are becoming an increasingly relevant presence in our everyday lives.

These plants and flowers speak about life as a process of incessant renovation, but also about death as the background that‚Äôs always there and makes life possible. This spectral vegetation seems to thrive precisely at the verge between both worlds.
_______________


This work is animated and will adapt to any screen size. It generates a never-ending ring of algorithmic foliage, which never repeats itself, and is different for each token. The image preview is triggered after the first five plants or flowers.
Made with p5.js

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture

metadata.name: Viral Refraction #28
metadata.description:
"Viral Refraction" is a mesmerizing generative art piece that offers a unique perspective on the ongoing pandemic. 

The close-up view of different variants of the COVID-19 virus is rendered in an abstract and dynamic composition, with the use of vibrant colors and intricate shapes to create a sense of movement and depth. 

This artwork highlights the unique characteristics of variants and evokes a sense of uncertainty and unpredictability that has become synonymous with the ongoing pandemic. 

This generative piece serves not only as a visual representation of the COVID-19 variants but also as a reflection on the challenges posed by the virus and its impact on the world. It's a conversation starter that is sure to leave a lasting impression on all who view it.

Disclaimer:
The use of the variant names in this artistic project are purely for the sake of creating a visual representation of the virus. This artwork is not meant to provide any scientific or factual information about viruses and should not be used for any medical or research purposes. The artist's interpretation of the virus is solely for creative expression and is not intended to reflect actual characteristics of the virus.

-----
* What/How *

2 560 000 particles are subjected to a succession of 64 energy bursts which scatters the points through space. 
The algorithm then stores 3 configurations of points, forming an entangled coherent system.
After few seconds multiple observation modalities are then selected sequentially to allow for dynamic and contemplative visualization.

-----
* Mint preview *

Minter will get a 2160x2160 PNG bitmap and an infinite randomly deterministic animation.

-----
* Technics *

This experience is designed to be executed on a recent GPU (>2016) and displayed on 16/9 screens from FHD to 8K+ (1920x1080 ‚Üí 7680x4320) at 60FPS for infinite duration.

- JavaScript / ThreeJS / WebGL / GLSL
- Unique generative, random and determinist animation (animation is seeded by the fxhash mint hash)
- Infinite animation
- Animation sequences duration between 6 and 60 seconds.

-----
* Controls *

Keyboard "Space" : take a PNG capture of the current view frame (same ratio as window, max 1920x1080)

Keyboard "X"¬†: skip current animation sequence / next sequence

-----
* URL modifiers *

"&fastdemo=on"
Forces animation sequences to last 10 seconds instead of random durations.

"&slow=on"
Forces animation sequences to last 1 minute instead of random durations.

"&static=on"
Disables animation automatic start. Press "X" to start animations.
